Preheat your #oven{} to 150°C. Halve, peel and finely slice the @echalion shallot{1}(peeled and finely sliced). Roughly chop the @dill{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). Zest the @lemon{1} then chop into wedges. Heat a drizzle of @oil{} (or a knob of @butter{} if you have some) in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat. Add the shallot and cook, stirring occasionally, until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pour the @water{750%ml} into a #saucepan{} and stir in the @vegetable stock powder{1%tbsp}. Bring to the boil, stirring to dissolve the stock powder, then reduce the heat to the lowest setting. Halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125} and pop them on a lined #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{} and season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{}. Spread out in one layer and pop on the top shelf of your oven to roast until soft and caramelised, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Stir the @arborio rice{175%g} into the frying pan and cook for ~{1%minute}. Stir in a ladle of stock. When the stock has been absorbed by the rice, stir in another ladle of stock. Keep the pan on medium heat and continue stirring in stock, letting it absorb each time. The cooking time should take ~{20-25%minutes} and your risotto is done when your rice is 'al dente' - cooked through but with a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle.

Roughly 3-4 mins before your risotto is done, carefully stir through the @smoked fish mix{215%g}.

> The fish is cooked when opaque in the middle and the prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

When your risotto is finished and the fish is cooked through, remove the frying pan from the heat. Gently stir through the lemon zest, @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g} and half the dill. Season to taste with salt and pepper and add a squeeze of lemon juice.

Serve the risotto in #bowls{} topped with the roasted cherry tomatoes and a sprinkling of dill. Finish with any remaining lemon wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!